Holding Zoe Lee while listening to my dads oldest friends and customers speak about him at his celebration of life, continued to drive home just how wild it is to welcome new life while mourning the loss of him. I continue to process and grieve, while at the same time holding so much joy and gratitude for this baby bird, who wouldn’t be here without him. 

Thank you to everyone who came out, who shared a kind word and remembered him for the kind, grumpy and hilarious man he was. He would have loved you Zoe, and I will make sure you know him because his energy is still here, his wit and his charm still so fresh in all of our minds and hearts.

“When I die I’ll have a big bash at the Sorrento, and all my friends will be there.” We were there dad. And you would have loved it.
Puerto Rico with baby girl sure hits different. ♥️🌴🫶
My favorite wedding date. Sorry @joelschneider 😉🌴♥️

1 year and my whole heart. I miss you everyday dad. 🤍

New year, same me.✨This years word? Grace. Giving myself grace to slow down and be more present. Less hustle, more sweetness. Time is a thief and this year I plan on taking my time with the moments I want to remember. Happy new year my friends, I hope it’s sweet and I hope it’s slow. All of my love. ☁️ ☁️☁️
On the eve of our anniversary, a reminder to love on all the good dads a little bit extra today and everyday. Thankful for this one and all that he does. 🫶 Happy Wednesday. ♥️

If I’m being real it’s been hard to not get lost in the world of comparison on social media lately. Seeing new moms that “bounce back” so quickly and I’m over here like where’s my bounce back. 

For me pregnancy was tough. Losing a parent, GD, super bad carpel tunnel and a breech babe that resulted in a c section…it was hard. Six months after I still feel like I’m postpartum. I still haven’t bought myself new pants even though I should. I’m still losing clumps of hair and wonder when I’ll feel like some version of myself again. I’m starting over in every sense of the word. 

Moments like these though. Stripped down strolls with nothing but sunlight and my girl, I’m starting to realize this new me…she’s not so bad.  After all, I’ve always been a fan of the long game anyway. Happy six months baby girl, I couldn’t love you more. ♥️

This posture, seemingly the simplest of things but oof, what a milestone for me to get back to.

I’ve said it before and I’ll say it again, wrist health is wealth. Out of all the pregnancy side effects, the wrist pain was the hardest one for me to overcome. I say overcome like being postpartum has an end date, but postpartum is forever my friends. 

Breastfeeding, carpal tunnel, gestational diabetes and having Zoe airlifted out of me has left me feeling like I’m starting completely over. Feeling proud of how far I’ve come and for allowing myself to go at my own pace getting back to my strength. I’m prioritizing the little things right now and doing my best to not have so much guilt wrapped around doing things like staying home. Taking that nap with the babe. Spending the morning drinking coffee slowly. Resisting the urge to set an alarm and hit the gym every single day. Waking up with my daughter right now takes priority. Making sure I’m around when she goes to sleep is a gift. 

In the moments where you feel pressured to move faster and get back to the hustle I encourage you to ask yourself why. This time with our babes will be here and gone in an instant so if you can, give yourselves permission to pause. The rest can wait. Hope Sunday is good to you friends.✌️ 

📷: @thejeffreid

The other day I asked y’all about when you stopped breastfeeding. At the time, I was feeling a little overwhelmed by the thought of it as breastfeeding has been such a point of connection for me personally as a mom. Yes, there are moments where I struggle with the side effects - things like acne, not being able to run, wondering what it would be like to take a night away and get out of town…it’s all such a personal journey. It’s also so different for every parent in terms of when they say when or what their situation is. 

So many of you responded. Within the many conversations I had with y’all I realized I’m definitely not ready, and I’m so grateful so many of you reached out. I’m hopeful that when Zoe’s ready she will let me know. I told y’all I would share the responses so pls check my stories if you’re feeling called to do so. Thank you all so much for your guidance and opinions. This network of women on here never ceases to amaze me. Love y’all. 🫶

📷: @mollymoormeier

Mom. 

My anchor. My world. My constant conversation. My person I always come to. Doesn’t matter the day. Doesn’t matter the time. You’re always there. 

You can tell how I am the moment you hear me say hello. You are the one who cares most when I’m sick. When I’m sad. When I’m scared. You are my person. My mother. My best friend. My life line. 

I want to thank you for raising me the way that you did. For teaching me to be who I am. For encouraging me to follow my dreams but be careful as I do so. For teaching me to love hard but protect my heart, because it has value. To trust my instincts, my gut, and you. To wear sunscreen and stop getting tattoos. To wear the right bra and drink water. I promise mom I’ll still try to learn how to cook. I really will. 

I will think of you every time I plant a garden. Every time I see a ferry boat. Every time I see a typo. Every time I see green onions. Every time I eat sourdough bread. Every time Zoe flashes me a look and I see you in her eyes. Every time I open my eyes. Every day. All the time. Mom I will think of you always. 

Words can’t express the love I have for you. I’ve told you I love you over the last few days so many times I feel like I need a new and stronger word for love.

Grandma Lea. I’m so glad Zoe got to know you. I’m so glad she will carry your name. I will teach her everything that you taught me. I will read her books and tell her what eye is. Where her nose is. I will teach her everything. I will carry this unbelievable love I have for you and I will love her just as fiercely as you have loved me. You taught me how. You taught me how to be a mom. And for that I am forever thankful. Mom thank you for being my mom. For being my world. For teaching me what it means to love. 

Tell dad hi. I know he will be happy to see you. I will love you mom. Always and forever.

To my darling girl, happy first birthday. You, my little Zoe Lee, are the reason I’m upright. Your smile, your dance moves, your spirit and sparkle are my whole world. In my most challenging season, you are my light. Thank you for choosing me as your mama. I can’t believe you are one. ⭐️🐠
Thankful is an understatement. ☝🏼

I’m going to be really honest, the best feedback I’ve received over the last few weeks is it’s okay to not be okay. The truth of the matter is grief changes you. Losing both parents within the span of 17 months so suddenly and so horribly, changed me. Losing my dad was devastating, losing my mom feels like I’ve lost my soul. 

I’ve been taking some time. Reacessing my life. My priorities. My relationships. My work…all of it. I’d be lying if I didn’t say many days it feels like I’m drowning in grief. The grief, it’s extraordinary. The road back most days feels impossible.

It’s okay to not be okay. And it’s okay to take your time. I’ll be back teaching on Friday, slowly making my way back to full time. If I could wear a name tag that said “please handle with care” I would. But for now just know, I’ll be there doing my best. Sending y’all love. Tell the people you love just how much you love them. Don’t wait. 

See you soon. ♥️

I’ve been writing. Every memory, every moment I can remember. I spent days (and many long nights) recently searching online for stories that sounded like mine. For anything that I could see myself in…stories of loss. Stories of hope. Stories of people who have gone through similar things. 

I’ve been writing. And while I have no idea what I’ll do with the words for now it seems to be one of the only things that is helping. Thousands of words describing a week I could have never imagined. It’s wild how in life there are certain moments that can be so unbelievably painful that you could have never imagined living through them let alone surviving. After the dust has settled and all you are doing is trying to heal you also never want to forget. Every moment. Every detail. Every single part of it. No matter how painful it is to see it in front of you, it’s proof that it happened. That you were there…and maybe even more important the fact that you are still here.
My very own earth angel. ☀️
New beginnings. 🌱

Because joy is important. 🫶

I am absolutely thrilled to share the exciting news that I will be leading the Take Care 200HR this winter at my beloved second home, @takecareyoga alongside our incredible team. After dedicating the past twelve years to teaching and guiding numerous teacher trainings, this opportunity holds a truly special place in my heart.

Take Care's unwavering mission has always been to foster an environment where talented and diverse teachers can flourish, and this teacher training embodies that vision. It's truly awe-inspiring to witness our trainees transformation from student to teacher, with their OG mentors at Take Care always right by their side every step of the way.

Concerned about the financial aspect? At Take Care, we wholeheartedly believe in making the practice accessible to all who are passionate about deepening their journey. While all of our scholarship spots have been filled, we offer flexible payment plans, ensuring that everyone has the opportunity to participate. 🌈

✨If you're curious and eager to learn more, I warmly invite you to join me as my guest in one of my classes. Let's connect, send me a message. All the necessary information can be found in my profile.

🫶This winter, broaden your horizons, become a certified yoga teacher, and become an integral part of the extraordinary community that is Take Care.♥️

My Josie girl. It’s hard to find the words when I feel like so much of what I’ve written as of late are goodbyes to the ones I have loved the most. 

My very best friend. My forever hiking partner, boyfriend judger, and protector through and through. I thought you were immortal. I truly can’t wrap my head around the fact that you are no longer here. You’ve been by my side for 16 years. Every apartment, every relationship, all the highs and all my lows, you were there. While I can’t imagine my life without you in it, I feel so lucky that I got to walk alongside you for as long as I did. 

I will love you my girl. For the rest of my days. You will always be my first love. I’ll see you on the other side. Rest easy Jo.

Things that bring me joy as of late. 💫 

Thank you to everyone who has messaged, DM’d, texted, and called about Josie. Hearing from so many people from different parts of my life makes me reflect on how legendary Josie was and will always be for me. It’s the end of an era, but knowing she was loved eases the heart ache of losing her. Thankful for my sweet fam who’s been by my side through it all. Love y’all. ♥️

When I was 25 and decided to do a teacher training I ended my relationship, quit my job, moved all my stuff into a storage unit, and gave up my apartment. I spent three transformative months in Bali studying yoga, gaining a wealth of knowledge about the practice. However, I felt disconnected from a community. It felt like starting over, and although there's a time and place for that, I realized the value of having a supportive community to fall back on. I was lost, and it took me a considerable amount of time and multiple teacher trainings to find my path forward.

This January 31st we begin our third teacher training at Take Care. What sets this training apart is its ability to work with your life, rather than requiring you to adjust your entire world to accommodate it. But the true magic lies in the sense of community it fosters. I've witnessed countless friendships blossom from these trainings; if I had a nickel for each one, well I’d have a lot of nickels. 😉 Ultimately, it's not just about the yoga; it's about the incredible power of community.

Join me this winter for a very special deep dive into the practice and the human experience. Take care. ✌️

The first teacher training I facilitated at Take Care I was pregnant and it ended three weeks before I had Zoe. The second I was newly postpartum, pumping while facilitating. Students got pretty used to the noise of the pump by the end of it. 😂 In the last two years I have hosted three retreats, led two trainings, lost two parents suddenly and tragically, said goodbye to my dog of 16 years, and welcomed my beautiful daughter. Oh, and the whole opening a small (breath based) business during a global pandemic. The thing about life is, it doesn’t slow down because your life sets fire.

None of it was easy. However having two other recent parents who were also pumping and navigating new motherhood in our last training was a godsend. We were in it together. I wasn’t alone, and you won’t be either.

In the moments when I feel like I’m out to sea and surrounded by wreckage, Take Care has been my anchor. The community– a life raft and my forever constant. Teaching has always had a way of reminding me who I am, even in the hardest of times. 

Life is beautiful. And life is devastating. But I’m here to remind you, you are not alone. 

Questions about training? Send me a message. I’m here. Always. Have a good day friends. Take care of each other.✌️
A moment I never want to forget. Happy Christmas Zoe Lee.✨
